After running for a while my LCD shows garbled leftover digits — e.g. a value like '25.3' briefly becomes '5.31' looking wrong when the new number is shorter than the old one. Here's my code, what's wrong and how do I fix it?

```cpp
#include<LiquidCrystal_I2C.h>
#include<DHT.h>
#define DHT_PIN 2
#define DHTTYPE DHT11
DHT dht(DHT_PIN,DHTTYPE);
LiquidCrystal_I2C lcd(0x27, 16, 2);
void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
  lcd.init();
  lcd.backlight();
  lcd.begin(16, 2);
  dht.begin();
  lcd.setCursor(0, 0);
  lcd.print("DHT IS READY!");
  delay(3000);
  lcd.clear();
  lcd.setCursor(0,0);
  lcd.print("INITIALIZING...");
  delay(2000);
  lcd.clear();
  lcd.print("READING....");
  delay(2000);
  lcd.clear();
}
void loop() {
  delay(2000);
  float h = dht.readHumidity();
  float t = dht.readTemperature();
  if (isnan(h) || isnan(t)) {
    lcd.clear();
    lcd.setCursor(0, 0);
    lcd.print("Sensor Error");
  } else 
  {
   lcd.setCursor(0, 0);
   lcd.print("HUMIDITY: ");
   lcd.print(h, 1);
   lcd.print(" %");
   lcd.setCursor(0, 1);
   lcd.print("TEMP: ");
   lcd.print(t, 1);
   lcd.print(" C");
   delay(10000);
   lcd.clear();
  }
}
```

The bug is that `lcd.print()` only writes the new characters starting at the cursor position — it does not clear anything after them. When a new reading has fewer characters than the previous one (e.g. going from `"25.3"` to `"9.8"`), the trailing characters from the old value are left on screen because nothing overwrote them.

Two fixes:
1. Call `lcd.clear()` every cycle before printing — simple, but causes a visible flicker each update since the whole screen blanks briefly.
2. Print fixed-width strings so the new text always fully covers the old text. This is the better option:

```cpp
char line1[17];
snprintf(line1, sizeof(line1), "HUMIDITY: %4.1f%%", h);
lcd.setCursor(0, 0);
lcd.print(line1);
```

`%4.1f` pads the number to a minimum width of 4 characters (including the decimal point), so shorter values are padded with leading spaces instead of leaving old digits behind, and there's no flicker.

Add print statements inside the success branch of `loop()`, right after the readings are taken:

```cpp
Serial.print("Humidity: ");
Serial.print(h, 1);
Serial.print(" %  Temp: ");
Serial.print(t, 1);
Serial.println(" C");
```

Place this before the LCD print calls so serial output isn't delayed by the 10 s display hold. This is useful for logging or debugging without needing the LCD attached.

`0x27` is the I2C address of the PCF8574 (or PCF8574A) I/O expander chip on the LCD's I2C backpack — the chip that lets the LCD be driven over 2 wires (SDA/SCL) instead of the usual 6+ parallel pins. The address is set by three address pins (A0-A2) on the chip, usually via solder jumpers on the backpack board, which is why different modules ship with different defaults — 0x27 and 0x3F are the two most common.

If `0x27` doesn't work, run an I2C scanner sketch to find the actual address instead of guessing:

```cpp
#include <Wire.h>
void setup() {
  Wire.begin();
  Serial.begin(9600);
  for (byte addr = 1; addr < 127; addr++) {
    Wire.beginTransmission(addr);
    if (Wire.endTransmission() == 0) {
      Serial.print("Found device at 0x");
      Serial.println(addr, HEX);
    }
  }
}
void loop() {}
```

Then update `LiquidCrystal_I2C lcd(0x27, 16, 2);` with whatever address the scanner reports.
